[b][size=5]Unspin - Rudimentary Hot-File Tiering for Unraid[/size][/b]

Unspin automatically promotes your most-accessed files to faster storage (cache/NVMe) using a lightweight C++ daemon that watches file access in real time. The main goal is to have fewer disk spin-ups (hence the name), but we'll take the faster access, too ;-)

There's no explicit cold demotion - for now we rely on Unraid's mover.

[b]Make sure this does what you want! There's a dry-run mode; use it![/b]

[b][size=4]How It Works[/size][/b]

Unspin runs [font=monospace]unspind[/font], a daemon that uses Linux's [b]fanotify[/b] interface to receive events every time a file is opened or read on your array disks. It applies three configurable promotion rules:

[list]
[*][b]Small file rule[/b] - files below a size threshold get promoted after N total reads (e.g. promote a config file on first access)
[*][b]Large file - short window[/b] - N reads within M minutes triggers promotion (e.g. 100 reads in 5 min = streaming video)
[*][b]Large file - long window[/b] - N opens within H hours triggers promotion (e.g. 3 opens in 24h = frequently consulted PDF)
[/list]

Promotion is always deferred until all open file handles are closed, so readers (SMB, NFS, local) never lose their file mid-stream.

[b]Why these rules?[/b] Under ideal circumstances we would cache everything - but we don't have the space. We can't have a huge Linux ISO using up precious cache space if it's just held open for a few bytes of torrent upload. But of course that changes if it's being constantly read, or accessed on a regular basis. You'll have to play around with the rule settings to best match your own use cases.

[b][size=4]Features[/size][/b]

[list]
[*][b]Event-driven[/b] - reacts to each file read in real time via fanotify, no polling or cron
[*][b]Three-rule promotion[/b] - separate thresholds for small files and large files (streaming burst / periodic access)
[*][b]Deferred promotion[/b] - waits until all open handles are closed, so readers never lose their file
[*][b]Per-share cache pool routing[/b] - destinations follow each share's own [font=monospace]shareCachePool[/font] setting in Unraid, so different shares can promote to different pools. Shares with "Use Cache: No" or "only" are skipped automatically.
[*][b]Detected Shares table[/b] - the settings page lists every share with its current routing and a per-share Watch toggle to opt individual shares out
[*][b]Mover/rsync-aware[/b] - automatically pauses while Unraid's mover or rsync is running
[*][b]Per-pool fill guard[/b] - each pool gets its own fill % threshold; promotion to that pool stops once it's exceeded
[*][b]Dry-run mode[/b] - logs every decision without moving anything
[*][b]Exclude patterns[/b] - skip any path substring
[*][b]Rule toggles[/b] - each rule can be individually enabled/disabled
[*][b]Pause / unpause[/b] - stackable pause locks via [font=monospace]rc.unspin pause <name>[/font]; useful for backup scripts over SSH
[*][b]Live log viewer[/b] - auto-refreshing tail of the last 200 log lines in the settings page
[/list]

